$$, $$abddbdf703432c962cf27e26acc2175f014bc04409ac0dc9c19e3dc13a526249$$, $${"A": "8259731f90697ed0e844842b3e82a8b58c3e70257464c0f2450d0ea650590d71", "C": "d4fdf923ba776b98bda680220afe7660b2fb7f78e25f4cb026ad0b29031d9620", "D": "dc20bcfe322a953e027f20d35548e05c3d7f39dbfb3e122e5ea0b51bbd42c7f2"}$$::jsonb, $$Budget J-Books/FY27/Navy/RDTEN_BA6_Book.pdf$$, 307, $$2026-05-10T04:04:20.593176+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.pe_narratives (pe_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, accomplishments, planned_program, performance_metrics, other_program_funding, raw_text, content_hash, section_hashes, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$0605520M$$, 2027, $$The modern battlefield has been irrevocably altered by the proliferation of low-altitude aerial threats, particularly Unmanned Aerial Systems (UAS). This program element
directly confronts this new reality, ensuring the Marine Air-Ground Task Force (MAGTF) can not only survive but dominate in an increasingly transparent and lethal
environment. It funds the critical modernization of our Low Altitude Air Defense (LAAD) capabilities, providing an essential protective shield for our maneuver forces,
forward operating bases, and critical command posts against the full spectrum of aerial threats.

To counter the immediate and ever-present danger posed by enemy drones, this program is aggressively pursuing more lethal and survivable Short-Range Air Defense
(SHORAD) systems. A key component of this effort is the transition from the venerable HMMWV to the Joint Light Tactical Vehicle (JLTV) as the primary weapons
platform. This move provides our LAAD Marines with a vehicle that offers superior armored protection and the maneuverability required to keep pace with the ground
forces they are sworn to protect. This initiative is not a single upgrade but the beginning of a continuous modernization spiral, designed to field progressively more
advanced Counter-UAS capabilities and ensure we remain ahead of the threat for the foreseeable future.

Simultaneously, this PE addresses the more sophisticated threat of cruise missiles and other advanced aerial weapons with the development of the Medium Range
Intercept Capability (MRIC). This system is designed to provide robust, dedicated defense for fixed and operationally fixed sites?the critical infrastructure that supports
the entire MAGTF. While its primary mission is to defeat cruise missiles, MRIC also possesses a formidable capability against UAS and other aircraft that penetrate its
engagement zone.

Crucially, MRIC is not a standalone system. It is engineered to be fully integrated into the joint Integrated Air and Missile Defense (IAMD) architecture. This integration is
vital, as it allows the Marine Corps to contribute to and benefit from a comprehensive, multi-layered defense, ensuring that from the individual Marine on the move to the
most critical command installation, our forces are protected by a seamless and resilient air defense network.

The FY 2026 spend plan amount for GBAD: Medium Range Intercept Capability (MRIC) includes $3,782 thousands of discretionary and $35,901 thousands of
mandatory (reconciliation) for a total of $39,683 thousands.
Systems Development$$, $$High Powered Microwave C-UAS supports the assessment of technologies to counter swarms that can be integrated into the MADIS FoS. The MAGTF is at increased
risk of lethal air attack and fires coordination from next generation aircraft as well as significant advances from small UAS threats due to their rapid development and
proliferation by the commercial sector.

AI-Enabled Autonomous Weapons Station in support of Marine Air Defense Integrated System (MADIS) increases the accuracy and effectiveness of the current MADIS
Fire Control System (Remote Weapon Station). Furthermore, the advanced processing capability streamlines targeting operations, resulting in a quantifiable decrease in
gunner workload and enabling faster, more efficient engagements.

Autonomous Counter-UAS Defeat System for L-MADIS supports the added requirement to integrate a critical small UAS kinetic defeat capability. The overall strategy to
fulfill the required performance parameter includes an Engineer Change Proposal (ECP) to integrate a remote weapon system on the MK1 platform and integrate vendor
sensors with LMADIS organic sensors to close the kill chain for small UAS.

