(Command and Control vehicle), and a MK 2 (Early Warning / Electronic Warfare vehicle). The L-MADIS PoR replaces the systems fielded under a Joint Emergent
Operational Need. The L-MADIS provides the Marine Corps a capability different than that of the MADIS. The L-MADIS is transportable within organic Marine Corps
R/W aircraft, allowing Marines to face challenging operational scenarios during Marine Expeditionary Unit (MEU) operations. The L-MADIS protects the maneuver
force from the threat of UAS, Fixed Wing and Rotary Wing (FW/RW), and other airborne threats throughout the operating environment while maintaining Marine Corps
expeditionary requirements. L-MADIS PoR began fielding in 2Q FY 2026

Marine Corps Air Defense Weapons Systems also includes the Installations-Counter small Unmanned Aircraft System (I-CsUAS). I-CsUAS provides protection of
USMC critical assets on permanent and temporary installations from sUAS threats; primarily Group 1 through 3 commercial-off-the-shelf sUAS. This system enhances
force protection of critical defended assets on USMC installations in both CONUS and OCONUS locations. The system will detect, track, identifies and defeats sUAS.
Based on lessons learned during the Urgent Statement of Need (USON), it was determined that the most economical acquisition pathway for the I-CsUAS program of
record (PoR) is to procure the systems. The PoR systems replaced "one-for-one" the six USON locations while fielding to additional locations determined by the Marine
Corps.

Next Generation Short Range Intercept (NGSRI): The Stinger missile is the primary effector against short range air defense threats. However, the Stinger missile is
becoming obsolete for the future force. The Stinger missile has limited range against current and emerging air threats, and industry has diminishing capability to sustain
the current inventory and produce new materiel. The Marine Corps will be leveraging the US Army's efforts to pursue development of a new interceptor to replace the
Stinger missile. The strategy is to provide an interceptor with improved target acquisition, range, and lethality against the evolving threat.

O-CsUAS is a family of Military Operation Specialty (MOS) agnostic systems that provide the Marine Corps an additional layer to the defense-in-depth strategy of
Ground Based Air Defense (GBAD). The O-CsUAS family of systems is capable of detecting, identifying, tracking, and defeating small Unmanned Aircraft Systems
(sUAS). A capability that originated as an Urgent Universal Need Statement in 2024 for the dismounted Marine, has grown to include mobile platforms and forward-
deployed, fixed site locations. Taking a Middle Tier Acquisition approach across the dismounted, mobile, and Expeditionary-Fixed Site capabilities allows for rapid
prototyping and fielding while maintaining pace with the threat. O-CsUAS will integrate disparate Non Developmental Item (NDI) components into a common command
and control architecture to improve the situational awareness and force protection of adjacent maneuver formations.

Overall, Marine Corps Air Defense Weapons Systems funding increases from FY 2026 to FY 2027 to initiate several critical modernization efforts. This budget increase
supports the integration of a new Electronic Warfare (EW) solution to provide non-kinetic defeat capabilities, and the development of a loitering High-Power Microwave
(HPM) capability to counter adversarial UAS as part of a layered defense. The funding will also deliver hardware and software upgrades featuring a resilient scalable
architecture (RSA) to enhance system survivability and employment flexibility for commanders. Additionally, the increase facilitates the integration of multi-mode
programmable ammunition to improve effectiveness against small UAS and ease the logistical footprint, as well as radar and optics enhancements to increase detection
range and autonomous tracking against emerging threats.

