Description: Provides for the methodical assessment of defensive technologies against current and emerging
threats. Through advanced simulation environments and integrated threat modeling, this effort validates
technology effectiveness prior to major investment decisions, ensuring development resources are directed
toward the most promising solutions. By leveraging high-fidelity simulations early in the development cycle,
we significantly reduce program risk and maximize return on research and development investments across a
portfolio of efforts designed to address multi-domain challenges, including the defeat of unmanned systems, the
enhancement of maritime force protection, and the establishment of layered underwater defenses.

FY 2026 Plans:
In FY 2026 we will begin utilizing a high fidelity simulation environment and integrated threat system models to
evaluate the performance of current and future threats against potential technologies considered for maturation.
This information will help maximize return on investment for technology development.
FY 2027 Base Plans:
- Building upon our FY 2026 foundation, expand the utilization of high fidelity simulation environments and
integrated threat system models to evaluate the performance of current and emerging threats against a broader
spectrum of potential technologies considered for maturation.
- As part of the Transit Protection Program (TPP), begin maturing, adapting, and integrating the Vessel Active
Protection System - In Transit (VAPS-IT) by leveraging proven Army protection technologies for maritime
application
- Begin the development of the Counter-unmanned Integrated Radar for high Clutter Environments (CIRCLE),
a stand-alone radar system designed to detect unmanned systems by using advanced radar detection and
tracking algorithms
- Begin the development of Swarm Interdiction using Floating Threads (SIFT) - Cannon (SIFT-C), a novel hard-
kill C-UAS/C-Swarm approach that works by slowing or stopping the UAS propulsion mechanism

