                                                             Accomplishments/Planned Programs Subtotals               39.754       32.045      66.255      0.000       66.255$$, $$$$, $$The Ground/Air Task Oriented Radar (G/ATOR) is a multi-role, ground-based, expeditionary radar that replaces five legacy radar systems and provides the USMC
Air Defense and Air Surveillance (AD/AS), Counterfire/Targeting (Ground Weapon-Locating Radar (GWLR)), and Expeditionary Airfield Surveillance Radar (EASR)
capability. The AD/AS development effort was competitively awarded in 2007 and completed Milestone C in FY 2014. AD/AS achieved Initial Operational Capability
(IOC) in March 2018. Development of the GWLR capability was initiated in FY 2010 with a RFI to industry, followed by a Business Case Analysis (BCA) to select the
most cost-effective procurement strategy. The results of the BCA indicated that a sole source contract to Northrup Grumman Mission Systems (NGMS) was the most
cost-effective solution. Thus, the GWLR software development contract awarded in August FY 2015. GWLR achieved IOC in February 2019. The EASR contract
was awarded in December 2023 going through FY 2025 with testing beginning in FY 2026 through FY 2027. The Full Rate Production (FRP) Contract with NGMS
awarded in June 2019. FRP Lot 5 (Congressional Add) contract awarded Sept 2023 for 9 EASR systems. Other G/ATOR enhancements include Non-Cooperative
Target Recognition (NCTR), Naval Integrated Fire Control (NIFC), GWLR User Enhancements, Extended Range Mode (ERM) Kits, Communications Modernization,
Low, Slow, Small (LSS) Targets, the implementation of Multi-Domain Radar in a Contested environment (MuDRaCE), a Radar Tracker Software Enhancement (RTSE),
Mode S, Digital Receiver/Exciter (DREX), EASR Mode software development/testing, and development/testing of efforts such as Electronic Protection and a Mission
Planner tool, which are all necessary to increase both G/ATOR's and the Fleet Marine Force's survivability in a Peer/Near-Peer competitor environment. In order to
improve G/ATOR's reliability and sustainability, the implementation of a Pallet Communications Support Processor (PCSP) Engineering Change Order (ECO) has been
divided into FRP Lots 3-5, along with the retrofit of the remaining 29 Radar Systems in FY 2025 and FY 2026. Except for the MuDRaCE FOS, capability enhancements/
improvements will be awarded as task orders on the Northrup Grumman Mission Systems Sustainment Engineering and Logistics Support (SELS) contract, awarded 1Q
FY 2021, that will support the continued development of G/ATOR capability enhancements and the deployment, sustainment, and maintenance of delivered G/ATOR
systems. A follow-on SELS 2.0 Contract spans FY 2026 through FY 2031.

 The G/ATOR Block (GB) nomenclature has been removed, reflecting that the G/ATOR system is a single, common hardware solution that supports multiple mission
 requirements against a variety of threats through software enabled modifications.

