FMA testing via laboratory, ground and flight events will evaluate AARGM and AARGM-ER digital Anti-Radiation
Homing (ARH) seeker and Millimeter Wave (MMW) terminal seeker capabilities against threat systems to
evaluate lethality improvement options. FMA assessments will remain focused on emerging modern complex
threat systems as well as theater/country-specific systems of interest. Expect continued testing and evaluation
on advanced Surface-to-Air weapons and related IADS, jammers, and ARM countermeasures.

FMA procurements are an important element to enable threat system evaluations. Procurement of up-to-date
AARGM-ER test assets will be necessary to support fleet threat evaluations. Surrogate threat system HW
procurement priorities are driven by Fleet inputs through the ARM steering committee and intelligence updates
to prioritize efforts across ARM weapons tactics development.

Fleet engagement will also continue as a key element of testing, engineering, and analytical efforts, which
includes funding for threat assessment, algorithm update recommendations, operational updates, and integration
efforts. Fleet testing priorities include characterizing emerging complex threat systems in the field, so FMA
assessments can directly populate missile threat data libraries with updated attributes to enhance lethality for
AGM-88 ARM weapons.

FMA will also assess special project efforts to support over the horizon (OTH)/advanced kill-chain capability
development against threat systems.
FY 2027 Base Plans:
FMA will continue to maximize AGM-88 ARM weapon effectiveness against threat air defense systems through
laboratory, ground-based, captive and live-fire flight test events, data analysis, and systems engineering to
improve weapon employment lethality.

